and":"Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, England":"Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1201–1250":"about 1201–1250","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1201–1250":"1201–1250","1245–1307":"1245–1307","1197–1246":"1197–1246","1225–1274":"1225–1274","1149–1246":"1149–1246","1177–1205":"1177–1205","1274":"1274","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","Bef 1246":"before 1246","Abt 1246":"about 1246","1250":"1250","1205":"1205","1149":"1149","1225":"1225","Abt 1201":"about 1201","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1177":"1177","1307":"1307","Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England":"Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, England":"Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Talemasche was born about 1201, in Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard De Talemasche, was 53 and her mother, Avicia Taillard, was 25. She married William d'Anvers II in 1222, in Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1250, in her hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"Abt 1201–1250":"umbes 1201–1250","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1201–1250":"1201–1250","1245–1307":"1245–1307","1197–1246":"1197–1246","1225–1274":"1225–1274","1149–1246":"1149–1246","1177–1205":"1177–1205","1274":"1274","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","Bef 1246":"enne 1246","Abt 1246":"umbes 1246","1250":"1250","1205":"1205","1149":"1149","1225":"1225","Abt 1201":"umbes 1201","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1177":"1177","1307":"1307","Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England":"Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, England":"Stoke Talmage, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 12